nport, Steve Ascher and Jeanne Jordan, Michel Negroponte, John Gianvito, Alexander Olch, Amie Siegel, Ilisa Barbash, and Lucien Castaing-Taylor. By exploring the cinematic, personal, and professional relationships between these accomplished filmmakers, MacDonald shows how a pioneering, engaged, and uniquely cosmopolitan approach to documentary developed over the past half century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDocumentary films -- United States -- History and criticism. 0aDocumentary filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aEthnographic films -- United States -- History and criticism. 0aEthnographic filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095493940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954939/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles